questiontext.text:
Solve the following exponential equation by writing both sides as a power of the same number. Give your answer fully simplifed and as a fraction where appropriate.

\(\displaystyle {@aa@}^{{@pwr1@}} = \frac{1}{{@aa^2@}^{{@pwr2@}}}\)

\(x =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution:

We first note that \({@aa@}^2 = {@aa^2@}\), so we can write the right hand side of the equation as a power of {@aa@} using rules of indices as follows:

\(\displaystyle \frac{1}{{@aa^2@}^{{@pwr2@}}} = \frac{1}{({@aa@}^2)^{@x-cc@}}\)

Expanding the bracket in the power, we get

\( \begin{align} \displaystyle \frac{1}{({@aa@}^2)^{@x-cc@}} & = \frac{1}{{@aa@}^{2\cdot ({@x-cc@})}} \\ & = \displaystyle \frac{1}{{@aa@}^{@2*x-2*cc@}} \\ &=\displaystyle {@aa@}^{-({@2*x-2*cc@})} \\ & =\displaystyle {@aa@}^{-{@2*x+2*cc@}} \\ & = \displaystyle {@aa@}^{{@2*cc-2*x@}} \end{align} \)

So, the equation becomes \({@aa@}^{{@x+bb@}} = {@aa@}^{{@2*cc-2*x@}}\) and we can conclude that \({@x+bb@} = {@2*cc-2*x@}\), which we can be solved to find the value of \(x\);

\({@x+bb@} = {@2*cc-2*x@}\)

Grouping the lies terms together and finding \(x\),we have

\({@3*x@} = {@2*cc-bb@}\)

\(x = {@(2*cc-bb)/3@}\).
